      <hedline>
        <hl1>Dining in London</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by Richard and Peter Harden, editors London restaurant guide, on Mark Bittman's Feb 11 article comparing prices in New York and their city (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: It's pleasing to read about our ''brilliantly revitalized dining scene'' in London, and it's true, as Mark Bittman says, that midday eating offers some wonderful bargains. As editors of Harden's Guides, including ''London Restaurants 2001,'' we would like to say that on dining generally, his cost comparisons are shaky. What strikes British visitors to New York nowadays is how expensive it is.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor: It's pleasing to read about our ''brilliantly revitalized dining scene'' in London, and it's true, as Mark Bittman says, that midday eating offers some wonderful bargains. As editors of Harden's Guides, including ''London Restaurants 2001,'' we would like to say that on dining generally, his cost comparisons are shaky. What strikes British visitors to New York nowadays is how expensive it is.</p>
        <p>Part of the problem is the trap  Mr. Bittman himself has fallen into.  He says that a $60-to-$80 menu in New York ''translates to a $100  meal including wine, tax and tip.''  Where does he eat? Take an $80 menu, add $20 for half a bottle of wine: you've already spent $100 before you add tax ($8.25) and tip ($16, and that would be modest). Total, $124.</p>
        <p>In London, wine is generally cheaper, tips are lower, and tax is included. The price differential -- if it exists -- is much less than first appearances might suggest.</p>
        <p>RICHARD HARDEN  PETER HARDEN  London</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
